SHARED FACILITY CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT
This AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITY CO-TENANCY
AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is made and entered into as of December 9, 2022, by and
among Moss Landing Energy Storage 1, LLC (“Moss Landing 1”), Moss Landing Energy
Storage 2, LLC (“Moss Landing 2” and, together with Moss Landing 1, the “Co-Tenants”), and
Luminant Power Generation Inc. (“Manager”), each a company organized and existing under the
laws of the State of Delaware.
RECITALS
A. The Parties executed a Shared Facility Co-Tenancy Agreement dated as of
November 13, 2020 (“Initial Agreement”). The Parties wish to amend and restate the Initial
Agreement to modify the scope of facilities subject thereto with this Agreement.
B. Moss Landing 1 owns and operates a 300 MW net battery energy storage
system, and Moss Landing 2 owns and operates a 100 MW net battery energy storage system (each
a “Moss Landing Project” and together, the “Dallas Energy Storage Project”). The Dallas Energy
Storage Project is designated as Queue Number 1472 in the CAISO Controlled Grid Generation
Queue. The Dallas Energy Storage Project is interconnected to the CAISO Controlled Grid at the
500 kV Moss Landing Substation.
C. The Co-Tenants are parties to a Large Generator Interconnection
Agreement (the “LGIA”), as Interconnection Customer, with Pacific Gas and Electric Company
(“PG&E”) as Participating TO, and the California Independent System Operator Corporation
(“CAISO”), dated March 31, 2020, as amended on November 17, 2020, and as may be further
amended from time to time, together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other
documents ancillary thereto for the purpose of securing the interconnection of the Dallas Energy
Storage Project to the CAISO Controlled Grid.
D. The Projects have a common Point of Interconnection to the CAISO
Controlled Grid, and the Co-Tenants share ownership and use of a 34.5/500 kV, 500 MVA stepup transformer (the “Shared Interconnection Facility”). The Projects also share (i) ownership and
use of an approximately 1,600 foot span of 500 kV transmission line between the transformer and
the Point of Change of Ownership and (ii) costs associated with the span of transmission line
between the Point of Change of Ownership and the Point of Interconnection with another entity,
Moss Landing Energy Storage 3 LLC, the governance of which is addressed in a separate
agreement. Therefore, the Co-Tenants are entering into this Agreement to specify their rights and
obligations as against each other with respect to the Shared Interconnection Facility.
E. Manager shall serve as the Co-Tenants’ authorized agent and representative
for purposes of administering the LGIA and the Shared Interconnection Facility on behalf, and at
the direction, of the Co-Tenants. The Manager’s roles and responsibilities are as set forth herein.
F. The Co-Tenants desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the terms
and conditions under which they will be co-tenants under the LGIA and share the LGIA and the
Shared Interconnection Facility among themselves and their Projects, to designate Luminant
Power Generation Inc. as the Manager under the LGIA in order to administer and manage the Co-
-2-
Tenants’ rights and obligations pertaining to the Shared Interconnection Facility and the LGIA
with respect to CAISO and the Participating TO, and certain other related matters.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and the agreements and
covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency
of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereto agree as follows:
AGREEMENT
ARTICLE I
DEFINITIONS
1.1 Certain Definitions. Capitalized words and phrases used herein shall have the
following meanings, or the meanings given in the Sections of this Agreement in which they are
defined, unless the text expressly or by necessary implication requires otherwise.
“Affiliate” means, with respect to a Person, any other Person that, directly or indirectly
through one or more intermediaries, Controls, is Controlled by or is under common Control with
such first Person.
“Agreement” has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement, and includes all
exhibits and appendices hereto.
“Applicable Laws and Regulations” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Business Day” means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, legal holiday or day when
banks in either New York, New York or San Francisco, California are required or authorized to be
closed.
“Bankruptcy Event” means, with respect to any Party, such Party: (i) voluntarily files a
petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding
or cause of action under any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or similar law, or has any such
petition filed or commenced against it by its creditors and such petition is not dismissed within
sixty (60) days of the filing or commencement or an order for relief is entered; (ii) makes an
assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors; (iii) otherwise becomes
insolvent, however evidenced; (iv) has a liquidator, administrator, receiver, trustee, conservator or
similar official appointed with respect to it or any substantial portion of its property or assets; or
(v) is generally unable to pay its debts as they fall due.
“CAISO” has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement.
“CAISO Controlled Grid” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Claims” has the meaning given in Section 2.5(a).
“Control” means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the
direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting
-3-
securities, its capacity as sole or managing member, its capacity as general partner, by contract or
otherwise. The term “Control” when used as a verb shall have a correlative meaning.
“Co-Tenant Representative” has the meaning given in Section 7.12.
“Dallas Energy Storage Project” has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement.
“Defaulting Party” has the meaning given in Section 5.1.
“Effective Date” shall be the date established by FERC in its order accepting the
Agreement for filing.
“Emergency Condition” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Event of Default” has the meaning given in Section 5.1.
“FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor agency.
“Financing Party” means any and all lenders (including the U.S. Department of Energy, as
a loan guarantor, and the “owner lessor” or similar entity in a lease financing) providing senior or
subordinated construction, interim or long-term debt financing or refinancing (including hedging
counterparties) or tax equity investors, for the development, construction, purchase or operation
of a Project and any trustee or agent acting on behalf of any such lenders or tax equity investors;
provided, however, that the Co-Tenants may agree by separate written agreement or instrument
that another Person shall have the rights of a “Financing Party” hereunder.
“Force Majeure” means (i) with respect to the LGIA and the Interconnection Facilities,
“Force Majeure” as defined in the LGIA, and (ii) in all other cases, any act, casualty or occurrence,
condition, event or circumstance of any kind or nature not reasonably within the excused party’s
control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures, including: (A) acts of
God or the elements (including fire, earthquake, explosion, flood, epidemic or any other similar
casualty or accident) or condemnation; (B) strikes, lock outs or other labor disputes (unless the
strike, lock out or labor dispute is directed solely against the party claiming the Force Majeure);
(C) the failure or inability to obtain permits and other governmental authorizations for reasons not
within the excused party’s control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures;
and (D) war, terrorism, sabotage, civil strife or other violence. Force Majeure expressly does not
include late delivery or breakage of equipment or materials or economic hardship except to the
extent caused by a Force Majeure event.
“FPA” has the meaning given in Section 2.7(a).
“General Default Cure Period” has the meaning given in Section 5.1.
“Good Utility Practice” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Indemnified Co-Tenant” has the meaning given in Section 2.5(a).
“Indemnifying Co-Tenant” has the meaning given in Section 2.5(a).
-4-
“Interconnection Customer” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities” has the meaning given in the
LGIA.
“Interconnection Facilities” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Interest Rate” means the lesser of (a) the prime rate as published in “The Money Rates”
Section of The Wall Street Journal (U.S. Edition), plus five percent (5%) per annum and (b) the
highest rate permitted under Applicable Laws and Regulations.
“LGIA” has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement.
“LGIA Costs” means Shared Facility Costs and, in addition, (i) all other amounts due and
payable by Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including amounts payable to CAISO or
the Participating TO, and (ii) all costs and expenses necessary or appropriate for the Manager to
incur or pay in connection with administering and managing the LGIA, including in connection
with Shared Facility Costs, affirmative covenants with respect to maintenance of the
Interconnection Customer’s Interconnection Facilities, communications with CAISO, insurance
and reporting.
“Manager” means initially Luminant Power Generation Inc., any subsequent Person
appointed as Manager pursuant to this Agreement, and their respective successors and permitted
assigns.
“Manager Representative” has the meaning given in Section 7.13.
“MW” means a megawatt or megawatts AC, as the context may require.
“NERC” means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or its successor
organization.
“Network Upgrades” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Participating TO” has the meaning given in the LGIA. The Parties agree that the
Participating TO is PG&E.
“Participating TO’s Interconnection Facilities” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Party” means any of the Co-Tenants or the Manager.
“Payment Default Cure Period” has the meaning given in Section 5.1.
“Person” means any individual or entity, and the heirs, personal representatives, successors
and assigns of such individual or entity where the context so permits.
“PG&E” has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement.
“Point of Change of Ownership” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
-5-
“Point of Interconnection” has the meaning given in the LGIA.
“Project” means, individually, either of the Moss Landing Projects.
“Project Controlled Assets” means, for each Co-Tenant, any of the assets comprising its
respective Project, the corresponding Project Real Property and related Project agreements and
contractual arrangements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Project Controlled Assets exclude the
LGIA.
“Project Real Property” means, for any Project, the real property interests utilized by such
Project.
“Pro Rata Share” means 75% for Moss Landing 1 and 25% for Moss Landing 2.
“Shared Facility Costs” means all amounts due and payable by Interconnection Customer
pertaining to the Shared Interconnection Facility under the LGIA, including amounts payable to
CAISO or the Participating TO.
“Shared Interconnection Facility” has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement.
“Surrendering Co-Tenant” has the meaning given in Section 4.2.
“Transfer” means, with respect to any asset, the sale, assignment, transfer, pledge,
encumbrance, transfer, or other disposition of such asset. “Transferee” shall be interpreted
accordingly.
“Undivided Interest” has the meaning given in Section 2.1.
“WECC” means the Western Electricity Coordinating Council or its successor
organization.
1.2 Rules of Construction. Except where expressly provided or unless the context
necessarily requires otherwise, (a) all references in this Agreement to a given Article, Section,
Subsection, clause or Exhibit is a reference to an Article, Section, Subsection, clause or Exhibit of
this Agreement, (b) the terms “hereof”, “herein”, “hereto”, “hereunder” and “herewith” refer to
this Agreement as a whole, (c) references in this Agreement to a given agreement, instrument,
document or Law is a reference to that agreement, instrument, document or Law as modified,
amended, supplemented and restated from time to time, (d) “includes” or “including” means
“including without limitation”, (e) references in this Agreement to “days” means calendar days
unless Business Days are specified; and (f) all personal pronouns, whether masculine, feminine or
neuter, include all other genders, the singular includes the plural, and the plural includes the
singular.
ARTICLE II
CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS
2.1 Co-Tenants; Declaration of Intention. The Co-Tenants hereby declare that their
relationship in and to the Shared Interconnection Facility and the LGIA is and will be that of
-6-
tenants-in-common, and that each Co-Tenant will have an undivided interest (“Undivided
Interest”) equal to its Pro Rata Share in the Shared Interconnection Facility and in the LGIA,
expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this
Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement will be deemed to constitute the Parties as
partners or joint venturers. The Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that the Projects will be treated
as a single Project under the LGIA and that no Co-Tenants may be added to the LGIA without the
consent of the other Co-Tenant, CAISO and the Participating TO.
2.2 Use of Shared Interconnection Facility and the LGIA. The Shared Interconnection
Facility and the LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects
to the CAISO Controlled Grid and to deliver electricity and electricity-related products generated
or otherwise made available by the respective Projects owned by each Co-Tenant (or by such CoTenant’s successors or permitted assigns) at the Point of Interconnection. No Co-Tenant may use
or permit the use of the LGIA or Shared Interconnection Facility in a manner that would reasonably
be expected to interfere with the use and enjoyment by any other Co-Tenant of such Co-Tenant’s
Project, or to violate Applicable Laws and Regulations; provided that a Co-Tenant’s use of the
LGIA or Shared Interconnection Facility in compliance with this Agreement shall be deemed to
not interfere with any other Co-Tenant’s use and enjoyment of its Project. In the event of a conflict
between the terms of the LGIA and this Agreement, the terms of the LGIA shall prevail.
2.3 Curtailment.
The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.3, direct the
Co-Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) when necessary in order to
maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of any Project; (ii) if the
Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to
an Emergency Condition; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant
to rights under the LGIA. Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the CoTenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible for interruptions, reductions or
curtailments under this clause (a).
With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical
power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 2.3(a), the Manager shall limit the length and
quantity of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly
necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of
Section 2.3(a) shall be made consistent with Good Utility Practice and to the extent commercially
reasonable during periods of low energy prices.
In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction
of CAISO or Participating TO, subject to Section 2.3(d), such curtailment shall be allocated in the
following manner until such curtailment is achieved:
(i) first, each Co-Tenant that is delivering test power shall reduce all
such deliveries down to zero; and
-7-
(ii) second, as provided in and to the extent applicable under
Section 2.3(d)(ii) below, until all such curtailments have been applied or any or all Co-Tenants
have been fully curtailed.
Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 2.3:
(i) The Manager shall curtail the Projects in accordance with the Pro
Rata Share unless (A) in spite of the Manager’s good faith efforts to direct the Co-Tenants to
comply with this Section 2.3, curtailment of interconnection services directed by the CAISO or
Participating TO is not otherwise achievable, or (B) a non-pro rata allocation is otherwise
necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each of the
foregoing clauses (A) and (B), Manager shall curtail the Projects on an equitable and reasonable
basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) and so that such non-pro rata allocation will
not result in a default under the LGIA; and
(ii) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or
reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant’s Project or portions of its Project or the
failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Tenant under the
LGIA or an applicable power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Tenant’s Project is the
cause of an Emergency Condition or is directed by CAISO or the Participating TO to curtail, then
all such curtailment shall be allocated first to such Co-Tenant’s Project and such Co-Tenant will
be responsible for all costs, liabilities, and damages resulting from such curtailment (subject to the
limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption
or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be.
Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of,
delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.3 upon notice from the Manager. In
the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager
may effect the same by direct action. A Co-Tenant that fails to implement any such curtailment,
interruption or reduction, shall be responsible for all costs and expenses related thereto, including
deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO.
2.4 Shared Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the
payment of all costs, charges and expenses incurred in connection with the LGIA and the Shared
Interconnection Facility in accordance with the following provisions:
LGIA Costs. As between themselves (but without limiting each
Co-Tenant’s rights with regard to contributions from other entities under any other agreements),
each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its Pro Rata Share of the LGIA Costs. In
the event that one Project becomes operational but no longer remains operational while the other
Project remains operational, the owner or owners of the Project that remains operational will be
responsible for 100% of the LGIA Costs unless the LGIA specifies otherwise. Such payment shall
be paid when due to Manager, and Manager shall pay such amount to the applicable parties, subject
to Section 3.1(a)(iv) in the event of one Co-Tenant’s failure to timely pay. Each Co-Tenant shall
pay its share of LGIA Costs without regard to whether such Co-Tenant has issued a notice to
proceed with construction of its Project prior to the date such payment is due to CAISO or the
Participating TO. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, any capital expenditures arising
-8-
out of any equipment or facilities solely required to interconnect a particular Project shall be the
sole responsibility of such Project and its Co-Tenant.
Collection and Payment of LGIA Costs. The Manager shall, as authorized
representative for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection, payment and reimbursement of the
LGIA Costs and other amounts relating to the performance of the Interconnection Customer’s
rights and obligations under the LGIA, including amounts due to or from the Interconnection
Customer under or in connection with the LGIA. The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing
the Co-Tenants their respective shares of such LGIA Costs and providing backup documentation
for such invoices. The Manager shall establish procedures for invoicing and collecting payments
from Co-Tenants in order to enable Manager to timely collect and pay for LGIA Costs and to
enable Manager and Co-Tenants to achieve the payment requirements under and in connection
with the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to audit, and receive periodic supporting
documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant
hereunder.
To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds
pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the
Co-Tenants (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which
event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant).
2.5 Indemnity.
Subject to the limitations provided in Section 7.11, each Co-Tenant (an
“Indemnifying Co-Tenant”) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenant (an
“Indemnified Co-Tenant”) and the Manager from and against any and all losses, damages,
liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation,
reasonable attorneys’ and consultants’ fees (collectively, “Claims”), which may be (i) imposed
upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or Manager or asserted against such Indemnified
Co-Tenant or Manager as a result of any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement
or the LGIA (including, without limitation, to the extent so imposed or incurred as the result of
joint liability under the LGIA), or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to,
property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of
the Indemnifying Co-Tenant or in connection with the ownership, use, operation, maintenance or
repair of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant’s Project.
Subject to the limitations provided in Sections 3.3(c) and 7.11, the Manager
shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims that may be
(i) imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of gross negligence, fraud or willful
misconduct of the Manager, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to,
property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of
the Manager.
2.6 Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and
assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, including any taxes and assessments
levied against such Co-Tenant’s Undivided Interest in the LGIA, except for any taxes or
assessments that are LGIA Costs, with each Co-Tenant paying its Pro Rata Share of such taxes or
-9-
assessments. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine,
interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided however, that
each Co-Tenant retains its rights under applicable law to seek a refund of such taxes and
assessments after having paid them.
2.7 Operation and Management; Insurance.
Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Project Controlled Assets
acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (i) in accordance with the terms of the
LGIA, (ii) in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (iii) in compliance with all Applicable Laws
and Regulations, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended (“FPA”), all
rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, and all laws and regulations
relating to land use, hazardous substances and environmental protection, (iv) in compliance with
the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the
same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (v) in compliance with the rules,
protocols, procedures and standards of NERC and WECC, and (vi) without causing a material
adverse effect on the LGIA.
Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA,
including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Costs arising under the LGIA. Each
Co-Tenant shall be an “exempt wholesale generator” as such term is defined in the Public Utility
Holding Company Act of 2005.
Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to the Manager as
a representative for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide the Manager such
information, certifications and other matters as may be required to comply with the obligations
under the LGIA.
Each Co-Tenant shall maintain insurance in accordance with the
requirements of the LGIA. If required by CAISO or the Participating TO, the Manager shall
maintain insurance in accordance with such requirements.
2.8 Joint and Several Liability. Notwithstanding any other provision hereof, each
Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that under the LGIA it is jointly and severally liable for (i)
any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the
performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA;
provided that a Co-Tenant’s joint and several liability under the LGIA shall not diminish or impair
any Co-Tenant’s rights to reimbursement or contribution from another Co-Tenant or any other
Person hereunder or under any other agreement, including this Agreement. Each Co-Tenant hereby
agrees to, promptly upon written request, reimburse, indemnify and hold harmless the other CoTenant for any cost, expense or liability incurred by such other Co-Tenant to the extent resulting
from its joint liability under the LGIA for such first Co-Tenant’s failure to make a payment when
due or perform any other obligation or duty of such Co-Tenant under the LGIA.
2.9 Disconnection. The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect (or
request the Participating TO to disconnect) a Project (1) as provided in Section 5.2, (2) upon
abandonment and decommissioning of a Co-Tenant’s Project as provided in Section 4.2, (3) if
-10-
necessary, consistent with Good Utility Practice for the operation and maintenance of any portion
of the Interconnection Facilities, (4) if the Manager determines, in its good faith discretion, that
disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency Condition or to otherwise prevent damage
or injury to persons or property, including to any other Project, the Interconnection Facilities or
the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues
affecting the Projects, provided that the Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give
the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible under the circumstances,
consistent with responding to the Emergency Condition or preventing damage or injury to persons
or property, or (5) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under
the LGIA. Unless Manager has in its good faith determined that it is unable to do so because an
imminent threat of injury or death to persons, damage to property or default under the LGIA exists,
Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Co-Tenant prior to or concurrently with disconnecting
its Project or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical.
2.10 Effect of Force Majeure. If a Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this
Agreement because of an event of Force Majeure, and if such Party promptly gives the other
Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in reasonable detail, specifying (to the extent then
known) the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the affected Party will be
excused from the performance of its obligations hereunder to the extent such performance is
prevented by such event of Force Majeure; provided that any Party affected by a Force Majeure
shall diligently take all reasonable measures to mitigate or eliminate the effects of such event of
Force Majeure; provided further that the suspension of a Party’s performance hereunder due to
Force Majeure shall be permitted solely for the duration of the effect of such Force Majeure and
solely to the extent that the suspension of such Party’s obligations does not cause a “Default” under
the LGIA.
2.11 Limitation on Number of Co-Tenants. There shall be no more than 2 Co-Tenants
comprising Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, and neither Interconnection Customer nor
any Co-Tenant may subdivide in any manner or form its interests in the LGIA or the Shared
Interconnection Facilities if such subdivision would create more than 2 Co-Tenants. Reallocation
of interests among Co-Tenants shall not be considered a prohibited subdivision.
ARTICLE III
MANAGER
3.1 Appointment of Manager; Manager Services and Limitations. The Parties hereby
consent to the appointment of Luminant Power Generation Inc. as the Manager under the LGIA,
subject to replacement as provided in Section 3.5 below. The Manager shall have no interest as the
Interconnection Customer in its role as Manager, but shall serve as the Interconnection Customer’s
authorized agent and representative for purposes of administering the Shared Interconnection

5.1 Events of Default; Default. The following shall each constitute a default by a Party
(the “Defaulting Party”) under this Agreement (each an “Event of Default”):
a Party fails to make any payment when due under this Agreement and such
Party fails to cure such default within ten (10) days (“Payment Default Cure Period”) after receipt
of written notice of such default;
a Party fails to perform any other covenant or obligation under this
Agreement in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such failure within thirty (30) days
(“General Default Cure Period”) after receipt of written notice of such default, provided if the
nature of the defaulted obligation is such that more than thirty (30) days are reasonably required
to cure such default, then the General Default Cure Period for such Event of Default shall be
extended by such additional time, not to exceed ninety (90) days in total after receipt of the written
notice of default, as is reasonably necessary to cure such default, provided such Party commences
to cure such default promptly, and in all events within thirty (30) days after receiving notice of
such default, and thereafter diligently pursues such cure to completion;
a Default (as defined in the LGIA) occurs as a result of the actions or
inactions of such Party (for the avoidance of doubt, after giving effect to any cure periods provided
in the LGIA in respect of the underlying Breach (as defined in the LGIA)); or
a Bankruptcy Event occurs with respect to such Party.
